Infection with the virus can be diagnosed provisionally on the basis of symptoms, although it is ultimately confirmed through reverse transcriptase polymerase chain reaction (rRT-PCR) of infected secretions or by computerized tomography imaging.
According to a Wuhan study comparing the polymerase chain reaction with computed tomography, computed tomography is much more sensitive than the polymerase chain reaction, although less specific, and many of the features in the images coincide with the processes of other diseases and pneumonies.
Since March 2020, the American College of Radiology recommends “not using computed tomography as a detection method or as a first-line test to diagnose COVID-19.”
The WHO has published several RNA testing protocols for SARS-CoV-2, the first of which was published on January 17.
